      <div xml:id="NA267-kiḷavi">
        <p type="edition">1. tōḻi kāppuk kaimikkuk kāmam perukiya kālattuc ciṟaippuṟamākac colliyatu. 2. varaivu kaṭāyatūumām.</p>
        <p type="translation" xml:lang="en">1. What the confidante said when [HE] was behind the fence at a time when guarding was excessive [and] passion increased. 2. It is also urging for marriage.</p>
        </div>
      <div xml:id="NA267">
        <lg type="edition">
<l>            nocci māvarum paṉṉa kaṇṇa</l>
<l>            vekkar ñeṇṭi ṉiruṅkiḷait toḻuti</l>
<l>            yilaṅkeyiṟ ṟēe riṉṉakai makaḷi</l>
<l>            ruṇaṅkutiṉai tuḻavuṅ kaipōṉ ñāḻaṉ</l>
<l>            maṇaṅkamaḻ naṟuvī varikkun tuṟaivaṉ </l>
<l>            ṟaṉṉoṭu puṇartta viṉṉamar kāṉaṟ</l>
<l>            ṟaṉiyē varuta ṉaṉipulam puṭaitteṉa</l>
<l>            vārēṉ maṉyāṉ vantaṉeṉ ṟeyya</l>
<l>            ciṟunā voṇmaṇit teḷḷicai kaṭuppa</l>
<l>            viṉamī ṉārkai yīṇṭupuḷ ḷolikkura </l>
<l>            livaimaka ṉeṉṉā vaḷavai</l>
<l>            vayamāṉ ṟōṉṟal vantuniṉ ṟaṉaṉē.</l>
            </lg>
        <lg type="translation" xml:lang="en">
<l>“Coming all alone to the seashore-grove,</l>
<l>where it is pleasing to reside, where was united to her</l>
<l rend="indent">the man from the ghat, where the multitude of big relatives of the crabs</l>
<l rend="indent">in the dunes, their eyes like the dark buds of the Nocci-tree,</l>
<l rend="indent2">are drawing lines among the scented blossoms emitting fragrance</l>
<l rend="indent2">of the Ñāḻal tree, as the hands stirring the drying millet</l>
<l rend="indent3">of women with beautiful sweet smile [and] shining teeth,</l>
<l rend="indent4">is very lonely.”</l>
<l>– I won’t come indeed. [Yet] I came.</l>
<l>Before [even] saying</l>
<l rend="indent4">“these, the sounding voices</l>
<l rend="indent2">of birds gathering to feed on various fish, so like the clear sound 	</l>
<l rend="indent2">of the small tongued bright bells, [are] his”,<note place="foot">Here we have a wonderfully elliptical main sentence: <term xml:lang="ta">ivai makaṉ</term>. We probably have to read it as "these [belong to] the man", the usual word-order being upturned because of the lengthy subordination dependent on <term xml:lang="ta">ivai</term>. The pragmatic interpretation is nevertheless dictated by the topos; i.e. it makes sense.</note></l>
<l>he came, [his] strong horses appearing, [and] stood there.</l>
        </lg>
      </div>
